[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":136},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance\u002F":112,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance\u002F":121},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190521\u002F1235809694\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":94,"date":95,"description":96,"extension":97,"lang":98,"meta":99,"navigation":100,"path":101,"readingMinutes":102,"seo":103,"standalone":104,"stem":105,"tags":106,"tldr":109,"updated":95,"url":110,"__hash__":111},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance.md","[JS Weird World] No.46 Quick Concept Check: Classical vs Prototypal Inheritance","1000316763",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":88},"minimark",[11,16,24,27,30,33,49,52,55,66,69,75,79],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance","Classical vs Prototypal Inheritance",[17,18,19],"p",{},[20,21],"img",{"alt":22,"src":23},"Classical vs prototypal inheritance","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FTXOsIxM.png",[17,25,26],{},"Inheritance just means one object uses another object's properties or methods. That's really the whole idea. A lot of people reach for elaborate analogies — cars, trains, whatever — when they explain this, but honestly the instructor's take is that just saying it plainly is way easier to follow.",[17,28,29],{},"So what are classical and prototypal inheritance? Classical inheritance is the kind you find in C# and Java, and it's super popular there.",[17,31,32],{},"Classical inheritance comes with a bunch of tools to work with:",[34,35,36,40,43,46],"ul",{},[37,38,39],"li",{},"friend",[37,41,42],{},"protected",[37,44,45],{},"private",[37,47,48],{},"interface",[17,50,51],{},"But you have to actually understand all of them before you know how to use them properly.",[17,53,54],{},"Prototypal inheritance? Things are a lot simpler here:",[34,56,57,60,63],{},[37,58,59],{},"flexible",[37,61,62],{},"extensible",[37,64,65],{},"easy to understand",[17,67,68],{},"Both classical and prototypal inheritance have their own pros and cons, so there's no clear winner. The point is, whenever someone's talking about inheritance, what they're really talking about is:",[70,71,72],"blockquote",{},[17,73,74],{},"one object using another object's properties or methods",[12,76,78],{"id":77},"image-source","Image Source",[17,80,81],{},[82,83,87],"a",{"href":84,"rel":85},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[86],"nofollow","JavaScript: Understanding the Weird Parts",{"title":89,"searchDepth":90,"depth":90,"links":91},"",2,[92,93],{"id":14,"depth":90,"text":15},{"id":77,"depth":90,"text":78},"JsWeirdWorld","2019-05-21 21:59:00","How is JavaScript's prototypal inheritance different from the classical inheritance you see in Java or C#? No car-and-train analogies here. This post gets straight to what inheritance actually is: one object using another object's properties and methods.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance","1",{"title":6,"description":96},false,"en\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance",[107,108],"JavaScript","JavaScript 全攻略:克服JS奇怪的部分",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-46-classical-vs-prototypal-inheritance\u002F","UCPR1zsTqvfXkKeWmVDuGmWpci8Nd_tt4d1SCsKx_H8",{"newer":113,"older":117},{"url":114,"title":115,"date":116},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-47-understanding-prototypes\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.47 Understanding Prototypes","2019-05-21 22:20:00",{"url":118,"title":119,"date":120},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjsweirdworld-45-objects-functions-chapter-wrapup\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.45 Wrapping Up the Objects & Functions Chapter","2019-05-21 17:30:00",[122,127,131],{"url":123,"title":124,"date":125,"readingMinutes":126},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F27\u002Fjs-weird-world-bonus-closures\u002F","[JS Weird World] Bonus: Closures, One More Time","2019-05-27 13:50:04","5",{"url":128,"title":129,"date":130,"readingMinutes":102},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-68-the-end-is-a-new-beginning\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.68 Wrapping Up the Weird Parts of JavaScript","2019-05-25 16:36:00",{"url":132,"title":133,"date":134,"readingMinutes":135},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-67-adding-jquery-support\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.67 Adding jQuery Support to Our Mini Framework","2019-05-25 16:19:00","2",1784011703556]